# State Management Guidelines

## Core Concepts

- Use TanStack Router for URL-driven state.
- Keep URL state clean and shareable
- Validate all URL parameters with Zod
- See [Core Concepts](mdc:.cursor/rules/core.mdc) for project setup
- See [Client Layer](mdc:.cursor/rules/client.mdc) for UI patterns

## URL State (TanStack Router)

### Basic Route with Search Params

```tsx
import { createFileRoute } from '@tanstack/react-router'
import { zodValidator } from '@tanstack/zod-adapter'
import { z } from 'zod'

const usersSearchSchema = z.object({
  page: z.coerce.number().default(1),
  sort: z.enum(['asc', 'desc']).default('desc'),
  filter: z.string().optional(),
})

export const Route = createFileRoute('/users')({
  validateSearch: zodValidator(usersSearchSchema),
  component: UsersPage,
});
```

### Usage in Components

```tsx
function UsersPage() {
  const { page, sort, filter } = Route.useSearch();

  return (
    <div>
      <UserTable page={page} sort={sort} filter={filter} />
      <Pagination currentPage={page} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### URL State Best Practices

1. When to Use URL State
- Pagination state
- Sort/filter parameters
- Selected item IDs
- View modes or layouts
- Search queries

2. When Not to Use URL State
- Temporary UI state (modals, dropdowns)
- Form input values (unless part of a multi-step flow)
- Authentication tokens
- Application preferences

3. Implementation Guidelines
- Always validate search params with Zod
- Provide sensible defaults
- Keep URLs clean and readable
- Use semantic parameter names
- Handle invalid parameters gracefully
